In their work, the scientists come to new 'improved' compounds prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarbs have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiple cages that consist of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and are coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Proud and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV-protease-induced HIV virus division, there would be no mature virus particles.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the virus's proliferation in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press report, which was published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the Science Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this range of substances against HIV protease was tested in the reagent glass, also against their resistant (resistant) variants obtained by HIV-infected patients.
The effect of the metalocarbs on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as on the clinically used medicinal products, but does not lose its effect on the resistance variants, which are often without effect.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as its other characteristics, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical design, makes the metalcarboreans interesting links for further research on the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, Head of the Laboratory for Structural Biology of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute for Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
