They learned these lessons so well that, as a government official in Shanghai, who began to change the course this summer, because of the low birth rate and the ageing population, and encouraged young couples to have more than one child, their answer was direct and final: "No way."
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
There is nothing left for a second child, said Wang, 31, a head of staff with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has produced two generations of notoriously thick, reconciled single children, who are lovingly called "small emperors," a population crisis is emerging in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 when this policy came into force, the UNO
The number of people aged 60 and over is expected to rise from 16.7% of the population by 2050 to 31.1%, well above the global average of about 20%.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with an educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-old and older people made up almost 22 percent of the reported inhabitants of Shanghai, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai City and Family Planning Commission, has said that couples of childbearing age need to have babies to "help reduce the ratio of the ageing population and alleviate the labour shortages of the future."
Shanghai will soon be "so old - but not as rich - as the developed countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
In the constitution of the country in 1978, China's one-child policy is probably the most controversial decision that has been introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Marital couples who are in breach of this policy have to expect huge fines - up to their triple annual salary in some regions - and discrimination at work.
Chinese representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical stress on natural national resources could be avoided, and human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural regions, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to drive away.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, which created an unnatural high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their position on one-child policy.
In 2004, they have allowed more exceptions to the rule - including city residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where both husband and wife have been single children - and in 2007 the tone of many hard slogans was reduced.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute for Population Research at the University of Beijing, said that government representatives have recently discussed more radical changes, for example, allowing couples to have two children with whom a partner is single child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters that taught families to have only one child have been replaced almost overnight by guidelines that describe in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for approval.
The city administration has sent out urban staff and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and to push information sheets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice to those who have more than one child.
The reaction was not exactly encouraging, said family planning representatives.
Deceptive reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outdoor areas of Shanghai said that a recovery in the applications of couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign, the urban districts do not report any change.
In the case of the municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000, as an example, only four to five applications are still received per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that the number of births expected for 2010 in the city will still be around 165,000 in spite of the campaign -- a little higher than 2009, but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee of the Shanghai community of Caolu, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want to have more children.
They want to give their first the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this was also legally allowed.
But they, like many Chinese, have only a small health and life insurance of the government.
Without a social network, they say that this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yeah, we're being robbed of the possibility of having more than one child.
But the problem is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the head of staff, said she only wanted a child, because she was also a single child. "We were the center of the family and we used to have everyone take care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and do not really want to. "
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old, who owns a translation company, said it more unabated.
For parents from the middle class with a double career, through which the birth rate is falling, he said, it is about being successful and for that one must be selfish.
The age group of today's 20-39-year-old grew up to see their parents fighting during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they do not want such a life for themselves, he said.
Also a single child, he said, makes huge demands on the time of the parents.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the question of space -- "You have to change your apartment," and life planning -- "When the child is 9 months old, you already have to have a resume for the best pre-schools."
Most of his friends are willing to go through this once, said Chen, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group proposes emission reduction plan
The UN-supported climate conference - which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations - has again, on Friday, set a priority for the publication of a document which will record an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrial nations having to face the greatest burden in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas control, has both identified the remaining obstacles and shown the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a trial that is going to take time, as next week more than 100 top politicians from all over the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, which was formulated by a UN working group specifically created for this purpose, is silent about the amount of money that rich countries should give to the poor countries so that they can master global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrial and large emerging countries can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of the global temperature increase that policy-makers would contribute.
The process is given great flexibility, according to John Coequyt, the leading representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has compiled a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's leading climate protection representative, Yvo de Boer, has called "the great whole."
It shows the basis for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent in the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also given the talks on Friday a boost to its commitment to providing USD 3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change - from the master of floods and droughts to the prevention of deforestation.
Friday, however, brought the same verbal fireworks that the talks had determined last week.
The US Climate Commissioner Todd Stern has rejected formulations that demand binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if they are not financed by the industrial nations.
This train announced that the Obama government is driving a harder line with China as a representative of the Bush government not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the rise of major emerging countries and taking measures, says Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern gave his opinion one hour after the statement by the Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei, who said that it was either a "lack of reason" to the leading American climate negotiator or "highly irresponsible" of him that he said at the beginning of the week that the United States would not help China financially to master global warming.
By the fact that the future economic direction of the great world powers is at stake, both within the industrial nations and between the industrial nations and the emerging economies have broken down.
The current fight also refers to the rescue of individual economies, as well as to the rescue of the planet, with China and the United States ordering themselves for their commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous measures.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the great powers are fighting for who should bear the cost of the braking of greenhouse gas emissions, as even the countries concerned have taken more aggressive action to take the countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions into account for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic domination will develop, says Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries that are most exposed to the effects of climate change indicated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding Treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say that the talks will best lead to a political agreement.
The alliance of small island states with 43 members presented a draft 24-page contract on the early Friday morning.
