Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1,50-metre-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had a long skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reporting Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was in a dry zone of the supercontinent of Pangäa on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of the dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging on the Ghost Ranch in the north of New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as new species
In the course of the excavation they carried together the remains of a total of five individuals.
Found confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "Dinosaur fossils from the trias are extremely rare, mostly only single pieces of fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
After the current teaching, the dinosaurs showed up for the first time about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these Ur-dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts are discussing when the lizards split into their three main development lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor, and also the birds, known as the "long-term" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plants of the eating Ornithischia (bird-basin saurus), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and stegosaurus.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, the researchers found, for example, evidence of air bags, as they also have the descendants of the Theopods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of the mammals.
In the case of Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also sometimes filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge sauropods later also had air bags and light-building bones, the common ancestor of both groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards first showed up there.
As a result, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America over all the parts of the earth, which were still a single land mass as a supercontinent of Pangäa.
The fact is that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot come from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three migration waves to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
