As the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare side line of the reptile tribe to the dominant farmers of the Earth's age, it is still mysterious.
During the Trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the air saurs and with many other lizards.
At the end of the Trias, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the relationship at the border from the Trias to the Jura died out.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass death that happened to survive the dinosaurs, but not the other reptiles.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the competition out of the field.
