The support for brake manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the ABS anti-lock braking system at the time and as it is now happening with the ESP stability control system, the emergency braking systems must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already a duty for all newly registered passenger cars and light small vehicles, for the rest of the vehicles a period of time was set until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure adopted by the European Union is to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents due to their operation.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical brake maneuver which the system detects on the brake pedal on the basis of the brake strength carried out by the driver.
However, this system does not exercise this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one third of the drivers involved in an accident did not get to the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not been fully inhibited.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake support, on the other hand, is used with the maximum force in the braking system and thus reduces the braking time and thus also the brake distance that a car is doing during the braking process.
According to a study by the EU, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving the damage of pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistants.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is expected that any fourth accident could be prevented with personal damage - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant shall exercise the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to minimise the damage.
